02:15.800 --> 02:17.800
            What makes me think 
            this belongs to you?

02:17.800 --> 02:19.000
    ( <i>gasps</i> )                   

02:19.000 --> 02:21.400
My jasmine scented              
oriental massage oil.           

02:21.500 --> 02:24.700
Oh, God.                        

02:24.800 --> 02:27.100
God, I thought                  
I'd lost this.                  

02:27.100 --> 02:28.800
    I found it wedged           

02:28.900 --> 02:31.100
 underneath the couch cushions  
         in my office.          

02:31.100 --> 02:33.800
        Ah.                     
         I don't think I want to
         know how it got there. 

02:33.800 --> 02:35.700
                     I'm kind   
                     of curious.

02:37.500 --> 02:38.700
Tell you what.                  

02:38.700 --> 02:40.900
Why don't you, uh, put that back
where you found it,             

02:40.900 --> 02:43.600
and that way, we'll know        
where it is when we need it.    

02:43.700 --> 02:45.900
    When hell freezes over.     

02:45.900 --> 02:47.900
     Well, that's perfect,      
'cause this stuff heats up      

02:47.900 --> 02:49.800
when you rub it in.             

02:51.700 --> 02:54.000
Now, what... what's wrong       
with her, you know?             

02:54.100 --> 02:57.300
    Maybe one of the chains     
  in her underwear is twisted.  

03:00.700 --> 03:01.900
     Afternoon, everybody.      

03:01.900 --> 03:03.100
             ALL:               
             Norm!              

03:03.200 --> 03:04.600
                            Hey.

03:04.700 --> 03:05.800
What's going on,                
Mr. Peterson?                   

03:05.900 --> 03:08.600
        Let's talk about        
 what's going <i>in</i>  Mr. Peterson. 

03:08.600 --> 03:10.100
            Beer, Woody.        

03:10.200 --> 03:11.700
  How's the job-hunting going?  

03:11.700 --> 03:13.100
     Oh, lots better, Sam.      

03:13.100 --> 03:15.600
Today I actually got turned down
for an executive position.      

03:18.600 --> 03:20.500
                 It's a good way
                 to lose that.  

03:21.900 --> 03:23.400
I'm sorry, Mr. Peterson.        

03:23.500 --> 03:24.900
You've been cut off.            

03:28.300 --> 03:32.300
 Oh. Okay, where's the camera?  

03:32.300 --> 03:33.400
        This is no joke.        

03:33.500 --> 03:34.700
     According to my books,     

03:34.700 --> 03:36.800
        you are way over        
    your credit limit.          

03:36.800 --> 03:37.600
SAM:                            
Well, what's the big deal?      

03:37.700 --> 03:40.000
What's he over--                
ten, 20 bucks?                  

03:40.000 --> 03:41.500
              837.              

03:42.600 --> 03:45.300
      But in other words,       
        under $900, huh?        

03:46.000 --> 03:48.400
            You can't cut off   
            one of our regulars.

03:48.400 --> 03:49.900
                  The poor guy  
                  is unemployed.

03:50.000 --> 03:51.800
FRASIER:                        
Look, Miss Howe, uh,            

03:51.800 --> 03:53.700
Norm here is                    
in a very delicate spot.        

03:53.700 --> 03:55.700
His self-confidence             
has been shattered.             

03:55.700 --> 03:58.300
Uh, what he needs from us now   
is help and support.            

03:58.300 --> 04:01.100
Isn't there some other way      
to resolve this problem?        

04:01.100 --> 04:02.500
Well, you could pay             
his bar bill.                   

04:02.500 --> 04:04.900
Norm, the woman                 
will not listen to reason.      

04:06.100 --> 04:07.900
            Maybe he could      
            work it off, huh?   

04:07.900 --> 04:08.900
          ( <i>laughter</i> )          

04:08.900 --> 04:10.100
          No, I'm serious. Whoa,

04:10.100 --> 04:11.600
whoa, whoa, hey.                

04:11.700 --> 04:12.800
        Listen, maybe there's   

04:12.800 --> 04:14.300
        some accounting he      
        could do for the bar.   

04:14.300 --> 04:16.399
Our corporation's books         
are handled                     

04:16.399 --> 04:18.399
by Franklin, Sussman            
and Gurwitz.                    

04:18.399 --> 04:19.800
                 Ooh, they're   
                 very good, Sam.

04:19.800 --> 04:21.600
            They canned me a    
            couple years ago.   

04:23.300 --> 04:24.500
                Please.         

04:24.500 --> 04:25.800
    ( <i>sighs</i> )                   

04:25.800 --> 04:27.900
Are you good                    
at anything?                    

04:27.900 --> 04:29.000
                    Yeah,       

04:29.100 --> 04:30.300
but you cut him off.            

04:30.300 --> 04:31.400
SAM:                            
No, no.                         

04:31.500 --> 04:33.200
Come on, don't you have         
any other skills?               

04:33.200 --> 04:34.300
                 I can barbecue.

04:34.400 --> 04:35.700
             Oh, hey, hey.      
                        Yeah.   

04:35.800 --> 04:37.900
                      NORM:     
                      All right,
                      well, I,  

04:37.900 --> 04:39.900
      uh... I did a little      
house painting in college.      

04:39.900 --> 04:41.200
  You know, to make ends meet.  

04:41.200 --> 04:42.300
( <i>laughs</i> ):                     
Norm, Norm, Norm.               

04:42.400 --> 04:44.100
Norm, I think                   
they're talking about a job     

04:44.100 --> 04:45.600
where you get, uh,              
paid with money,                

04:45.600 --> 04:49.000
not with little grain pellets   
dropped out of a chute.         

04:49.000 --> 04:51.400
    Cliff, you, uh, you got     
  something against painters?   

04:51.500 --> 04:52.700
( <i>laughs</i> ):                     
No, no, no. I...                

04:52.700 --> 04:54.300
I'm in favor                    
of hiring the blithering.       

04:54.400 --> 04:56.200
    ( <i>laughs</i> )                  

04:56.200 --> 04:58.500
Do... do you need               
any painting done around here?  

04:59.700 --> 05:01.400
             I guess you could  
             repaint the office.

05:01.500 --> 05:03.100
                Are you willing?

05:03.200 --> 05:04.600
It's been an awfully long time. 

05:04.600 --> 05:05.700
CLIFF:                          
Oh, yeah, yeah.                 

05:05.800 --> 05:06.900
It's gonna take you             

05:06.900 --> 05:08.500
        at least, what,         
     seven or eight seconds     

05:08.500 --> 05:09.500
     to relearn that skill.     

05:09.500 --> 05:10.500
        ( <i>laughs</i> )              

05:10.500 --> 05:12.000
'Cause, you know, Cliff,        
I'm beginning                   

05:12.000 --> 05:13.500
to pick up                      
a little thread here. Uh...     

05:13.600 --> 05:14.600
            Ah.                 

05:14.700 --> 05:15.800
Would you mind explaining       

05:15.800 --> 05:17.900
        this little obsession   
        you have about painters?

05:18.000 --> 05:19.700
                CLIFF:          
                Well, all right.
                Uh, well,       

05:19.700 --> 05:20.400
it's manual labor.              

05:20.400 --> 05:21.700
I mean,                         
it's beneath you, Norm.         

05:21.700 --> 05:23.700
Well, if you take a job         
like this, we're gonna be       

05:23.800 --> 05:25.500
on entirely different           
social strata.                  

05:25.600 --> 05:27.800
We'll have nothing              
to talk about, all right?       

05:27.800 --> 05:29.900
      Semigloss or enamel?      

05:36.500 --> 05:38.600
 Hey, Woody, would you close up 
        for me tonight?         

05:38.700 --> 05:40.100
    I got to get home.          

05:40.200 --> 05:41.500
    No problem, Carla.          

05:41.500 --> 05:42.900
By the way,                     

05:43.000 --> 05:44.200
I really am envious of you      

05:44.200 --> 05:46.100
    having a nice big family    
         to go home to.         

05:46.200 --> 05:47.900
Oh, yeah, it's great, all right.

05:48.000 --> 05:50.200
I got 11 people                 

05:50.200 --> 05:52.500
living under a roof             
that was meant for only six.    

05:52.500 --> 05:56.000
Gino's dog just had puppies     
on my side of the bed.          

05:56.100 --> 05:58.600
My daughter-in-law              
is driving me nuts, and somehow,

05:58.700 --> 06:01.200
my mother-in-law got a hold     
of our address.                 

06:03.200 --> 06:05.200
                 Puppies.       
                 You lucky duck.

06:09.100 --> 06:14.300
    ( <i>humming</i> )                 

06:14.300 --> 06:15.900
              You seem to be    
              enjoying yourself.

06:16.000 --> 06:17.900
        Oh, sorry. Uh...        

06:18.000 --> 06:19.000
     No, that's all right.      

06:21.800 --> 06:24.700
Oh, uh, you got a phone call    
here, uh...                     

06:24.800 --> 06:26.300
            Eva Ake?            

06:27.500 --> 06:28.400
I could swear                   
it was a man.                   

06:28.400 --> 06:29.600
Oh, well,                       
there's paint here.             

06:29.700 --> 06:31.200
Evan Drake. Uh...               

06:31.300 --> 06:32.700
                That's my boss. 
        Yeah.                   

06:32.800 --> 06:33.600
                What did he say?

06:33.700 --> 06:35.000
Well, he said, he, uh...        

06:35.000 --> 06:36.900
he wants you                    
to tear up my bar bill.         

06:37.900 --> 06:40.100
I... Well...                    

06:40.100 --> 06:41.700
I didn't think                  
I'd get away with that.         

06:41.700 --> 06:43.700
Uh, but, no, he said            
he's on his way over here.      

06:43.800 --> 06:45.300
Sometime, like, uh...           

06:45.400 --> 06:46.900
around nowish.                  

06:46.900 --> 06:48.300
                Now?!           

06:48.300 --> 06:50.200
              God.              

07:02.000 --> 07:05.700
Shall I, uh, comb my hair, too, 
     or will I be leaving?      

07:07.100 --> 07:09.400
This is just a business meeting.

07:11.800 --> 07:13.900
        ( <i>phone rings</i> )         

07:13.900 --> 07:15.100
                Rebecca Howe.   

07:15.100 --> 07:16.400
     Oh, hello, Mr. Drake.      

07:16.400 --> 07:17.700
      I thought you were--      

07:17.800 --> 07:19.200
             Norm.              

07:19.800 --> 07:20.900
    No, no, no, I know          

07:20.900 --> 07:22.600
        you're not Norm.        
          You're Evan.          

07:22.600 --> 07:23.900
                    What I meant

07:23.900 --> 07:25.500
          to say was--          
        Get out of here.        

07:25.500 --> 07:26.700
            No, no, no, not you.

07:26.700 --> 07:28.500
                  You stay right
                  where you are.

07:28.600 --> 07:29.700
                  No, I swear...

07:29.800 --> 07:30.700
            Get out!            

07:30.800 --> 07:33.300
                      Oh. Hello?

07:33.300 --> 07:36.100
                  Well, that was
                  fast, Mr. P.  

07:36.200 --> 07:38.600
Yeah, she got a phone call      
        from Mr. Drake.         

07:38.600 --> 07:40.800
Hey, Mr. Peterson,              
I really feel bad               

07:40.800 --> 07:42.300
about you being cut off.        

07:42.300 --> 07:43.900
                    Yeah.       

07:43.900 --> 07:46.200
You know, I remember            
the good old days               

07:46.200 --> 07:48.300
when you used                   
to come in here and             

07:48.300 --> 07:49.900
say something funny.            

07:50.000 --> 07:51.600
I'd pour you a beer.            

07:51.700 --> 07:53.200
You'd drink it,                 
I'd pour you another one,       

07:53.200 --> 07:54.400
you'd drink that, too.          

07:54.500 --> 07:55.600
                Yeah.           

07:55.600 --> 07:57.500
        Yeah, I remember, Woody.

07:58.800 --> 08:00.300
So look at that--               
hardly even touched.            

08:00.300 --> 08:01.600
                    Yeah.       

08:01.700 --> 08:04.100
I'll tell you, I don't          
normally drink beer, but, uh,   

08:04.200 --> 08:07.100
I just cleaned the taps,        
and I wanted to make sure       

08:07.100 --> 08:09.800
that everything was all right,  
so I had one.                   

08:09.800 --> 08:12.500
It was like a mountain stream,  

08:12.500 --> 08:14.600
only colder, fresher.           

08:14.600 --> 08:16.600
You know, sometimes             

08:16.600 --> 08:18.500
there's nothing                 
like a nice cold beer           

08:18.500 --> 08:19.700
to really hit the spot.         

08:19.800 --> 08:22.000
          Yeah, I think I read  
          that somewhere, Woody.

08:35.700 --> 08:37.299
You know,                       
I-I really like this color.     

08:37.299 --> 08:38.500
I think it's gonna really       

08:38.500 --> 08:40.100
spruce up the office            
quite a bit.                    

08:40.100 --> 08:41.900
                     ( <i>sobbing</i> )

08:41.900 --> 08:43.600
Again, it's just                
an opinion. Uh...               

08:43.600 --> 08:45.600
                     ( <i>sobbing</i> )

08:45.600 --> 08:48.000
Is there something wrong?       

08:48.000 --> 08:51.000
            ( <i>tearful mumbling</i> )

08:53.500 --> 08:57.200
Right. Well, yes,               
I understand, of course.        

08:57.200 --> 08:58.700
Here, here, have a seat,        
have a seat.                    

08:58.700 --> 09:00.000
Just relax.                     

09:00.100 --> 09:01.700
                    Oh, God.    

09:01.800 --> 09:03.700
        Here.                   

09:03.700 --> 09:06.400
          Some authority figure.

09:06.400 --> 09:08.000
                I'm sorry.      

09:08.000 --> 09:10.700
                It's probably   
                just job stress.

09:10.700 --> 09:12.100
    Oh, you shouldn't           
     be having job stress.      

09:12.100 --> 09:13.500
 You're doing a great job here. 

09:13.500 --> 09:14.800
  Oh, tell that to Mr. Drake.   

09:14.800 --> 09:17.200
He said I should consider       
     the last fiscal report     

09:17.300 --> 09:19.600
a personal embarrassment.       

09:19.600 --> 09:20.800
                     ( <i>sobbing</i> )

09:20.800 --> 09:22.500
    Norm, I need your help.     

09:22.500 --> 09:23.500
     Uh, you just started.      

09:23.600 --> 09:24.800
  You're-you're gonna do fine.  

09:24.900 --> 09:26.800
 Things are gonna turn around,  
            I swear.            

09:26.900 --> 09:27.900
Uh...                           

09:27.900 --> 09:29.000
         No, you idiot.         

09:29.100 --> 09:30.700
  My hair's stuck to the wall.  

09:30.700 --> 09:34.100
                    ( <i>sniffles</i> )

09:40.600 --> 09:42.000
Oh, great.                      

09:42.000 --> 09:43.100
                    No, no, it's
                    really...   

09:43.200 --> 09:44.400
                 It's not, uh...
                 not that bad.  

09:44.400 --> 09:46.300
                I paid big bucks
                to have Vera's  
                hair frosted.   

09:46.300 --> 09:48.000
                 Didn't turn out
                 half as good.  

09:49.700 --> 09:52.000
Well, maybe                     
I better take off.              

09:52.100 --> 09:53.700
When people are upset,          
they...                         

09:53.700 --> 09:54.900
they like to be alone.          

09:54.900 --> 09:56.800
      Nonsense. I'm fine.       

09:56.800 --> 09:57.800
    Talking about me.           

09:57.900 --> 09:59.500
  I'm feeling a little queasy.  

09:59.600 --> 10:01.300
        Oh, please stay.        

10:02.400 --> 10:03.700
            I mean,             

10:03.800 --> 10:06.200
     this office is a real      
    inconvenience like this.    

10:09.200 --> 10:11.000
        All right.              

10:11.000 --> 10:13.300
          ( <i>sniffles</i> )          

10:16.400 --> 10:17.700
Would you, uh,                  

10:17.700 --> 10:19.900
     would you like to talk     
about what just happened?       

10:20.000 --> 10:20.400
              No.               

10:20.400 --> 10:21.800
             Phew.              

10:28.800 --> 10:30.900
        ( <i>sighs</i> )               

10:30.900 --> 10:32.400
    You really do seem to be    

10:32.500 --> 10:34.100
    enjoying this job.          

10:34.100 --> 10:35.900
Yeah. Yeah, I actually do,      
        you know?               

10:36.000 --> 10:37.400
    I think painting is just    

10:37.400 --> 10:39.600
      so vastly different       
        from accounting.        

10:40.800 --> 10:42.500
This is real, you know?         

10:42.500 --> 10:44.900
This I have some control over.  

10:45.000 --> 10:46.400
I mean, when I look back,       

10:46.400 --> 10:48.900
        I finish a job,         
        I can say,              

10:48.900 --> 10:51.700
    "You know, I did that."     

10:55.400 --> 10:57.800
Door must have moved.           

10:58.500 --> 11:00.400
You know,                       

11:00.500 --> 11:03.800
    I think that this color     
    is the exact same color     

11:03.900 --> 11:06.300
 as Mary Lou Sebold's car coat. 

11:06.300 --> 11:06.900
              Who?              

11:07.000 --> 11:08.300
        This girl               
    I had an insane crush on    

11:08.300 --> 11:09.500
      in the third grade.       

11:09.500 --> 11:11.400
     Except she had no idea     
    that I was alive.           

11:11.400 --> 11:12.900
I used to leave                 

11:12.900 --> 11:14.000
     little notes for her.      

11:14.000 --> 11:15.600
         "I love you."          

11:15.700 --> 11:18.000
          And one day,          
I finally got up the nerve      

11:18.000 --> 11:19.300
    to sign one, N.P.           

11:19.300 --> 11:21.600
         The next week,         
      she was going steady      

11:21.700 --> 11:24.300
      with my best friend,      
    Nicky Petropolis.           

11:25.700 --> 11:27.200
         What'd you do?         

11:27.200 --> 11:29.100
         The only thing         
      I could do, really.       

11:29.100 --> 11:30.400
     I went over to Nicky,      

11:30.500 --> 11:32.500
     and I calmly explained     
         the situation.         

11:32.500 --> 11:33.900
    Then I sat on him.          

11:34.000 --> 11:35.500
        ( <i>laughs</i> )              

11:36.200 --> 11:38.500
          ( <i>continues laughing</i> )

11:38.600 --> 11:40.100
                        Oh, God.

11:40.100 --> 11:42.100
 I think that's the first time  
      I've really laughed       

11:42.200 --> 11:43.300
    since I took over here.     

11:43.300 --> 11:45.200
      Oh, it is, trust me.      

11:49.400 --> 11:51.700
 Why'd you tell me that story?  

11:51.700 --> 11:53.100
      Well, I don't know.       

11:53.100 --> 11:54.500
    It's kind of late.          

11:54.500 --> 11:55.800
          We're alone.          

11:55.800 --> 11:57.900
I'm a man, you're a woman.      

11:59.200 --> 12:00.500
 Maybe it's the paint talking.  

12:04.700 --> 12:05.800
                        Norm?   

12:05.900 --> 12:07.100
Yeah.                           

12:07.200 --> 12:09.400
      Do you find me cold?      

